{
  "answer": "**In Manusmṛti 10.4, the text explicitly defines the \"twice-born\" (*dvija*) varṇas as the three upper castes.**[^1]\n\nIt states: \"The Brahmana, the Kshatriya, and the Vaishya are the three twice-born *varnas*; but the fourth, the Shudra, is of a single birth; there is no fifth.\"\n\nThis verse establishes the classic distinction in the text: the first three varṇas—Brāhmaṇa (priests/scholars), Kṣatriya (warriors/rulers), and Vaiśya (merchants/farmers)—are \"twice-born\" due to undergoing the upanayana (sacred thread) initiation as a symbolic second birth, in addition to physical birth. The Śūdra (servants/laborers) lacks this rite and is thus \"once-born.\" This rule frames much of chapter 10's discussion on mixed castes, duties, and livelihoods.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/10/translation/#p-92e12d).\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 10, [full chapter](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/10/translation/).",
